Your posted class `TrafficLight.java` is part of an `Applet`. So it cannot be run on it&#39;s own.

Applets itself normally are embedded into a webpage and run inside a browser. See more about applets on [Oracles Applet tutorial][1].

To run it within an applet you could download the following files from [here][2]

 - [TrafficLight.java][3]
 - [PedestrianLight.class][4]
 - [PedestrianLight.java][5]
 - [TLApplet.class][6]
 - [TLApplet.html][7]
 - [TLApplet.java][8]
 - [TLApplet-conv.html][9]
 - [TrafficLight.class][10]
 - [TrafficLight.java][3]

The you can run the applet as:

    appletviewer TLApplet.html

To run the applet code from commandline without the appletviewer you need some graphic container where the applet can be executed.

An example snippet looks like

	import javax.swing.JFrame;
	import javax.swing.JApplet;

	class TLAppletFrame {

		public static void main(String[] args) {
			JApplet applet = new TLApplet();
			applet.init();

			JFrame frame = new JFrame(&quot;Applet in Frame&quot;);
			frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
			frame.add( applet );
			frame.pack();
			frame.setLocationRelativeTo( null );
			frame.setVisible( true );

			applet.start();
		}	
	}

To run it you have to execute (assumed the file `TLAppletFrame.java`is in the same directory as the downloaded files)

    javac TLAppletFrame.java
    java TLAppletFrame

